Recalling the very American ideal that labour rights are human rights
Congressmen Keith Allison and John Lewis proposed a bill on which trade union organizations are protected as civil law.
"Where trade unions are, there are middle-class jobs," says Allison, democracy from Minnesota, who is co-chair of the Congress of the Progressive Faction.
That's why I'm proud to present the Employee Empowerment Act along with the civil rights movement symbol John Lewis.
This innovative bill will provide workers with the same legal opportunity to discriminate against trade union organizations as other forms of discrimination by halting the forces of opponents of trade unions.
The amendment of the Labour Relations Regulation Act in such a way as to enable workers facing discrimination for participation in trade union organizations to seek justice before civil courts, and to receive compensation for damages and fines, a reasonable and necessary initiative.
But this is certainly not a radical initiative - at least by American standards.
In fact, the best way to figure out what Allison, Lewis and the co-sponsors of the bill are to remember a very American thought.
Despite the attacks by trade unions in recent years, in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states throughout the country, Americans once supported countries around the world in accepting, expanding and respecting labour rights.
There was a time that millions of Americans remember when that country was at the same time defending democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press and the right to organize.
When the United States occupied Japan after the Second World War, General Douglas McArthur and his assistants helped the country to adopt a constitution designed to guarantee that Hideki Todzie's paramilitary autocracy had been replaced by democracy.
While fully aware that workers and their trade unions played a role in forming a new Japan, they included a text that explicitly recognized that “the right of workers to organize, to negotiate and to collective action is guaranteed”.
When the United States occupied Germany after the Second World War, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his associates helped the Germans write a constitution that guaranteed that the fascism of Adolf Hitler had been replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers would need to be organized and heard in the new State, the Germans included an article that openly stated: “The right to form associations to protect and improve the working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every person and to every profession or activity.
Agreements which restrict or seek to undermine this right will not have legal effect; measures to that effect will be considered illegal.
When former Lady Eleanor Roosevelt chaired the International Commission on Human Rights, which produced the World Declaration on Human Rights, which in 1948 would be adopted by the United Nations as a world agreement, Roosevelt and the drafters included a guarantee that “everyone has the right to organize and join trade unions for the sake of his own interests”.
For generations, Americans have adopted as a valid basic provision that labour rights are human rights.
When the country advised other countries on how to create civil and democratic societies, Americans explained that the right to organize trade unions — and that the trade union should participate as an equal partner in collective bargaining with corporations and government institutions — should be protected.
At a time when those rights are being attacked in America, it is indeed wise to return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to organize and to be heard in a free and open society.
As Reverend Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago,
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the trade union movement has not undermined the power of the nation, but has increased it.
By raising the standard of living of millions, trade unions have miraculously created a market for industry and raised an entire nation to an unimaginable level of production.
Those who attack trade unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers the way it should be.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the expansion of the protection of civil rights to prevent discrimination against the organization of trade unions - is long overdue.
Keith Allison and John Lewis are reviving ideals that have historically expanded America and made the promise of democracy a reality.
