Anger has proved to be the most universal and functional human emotion
The hard expression of the face is biologically universal for mankind, and every organ and group of muscles involved in it is not accidental, but is an additional means of expressing power and threat, scientists in Australia and the United States have clarified.
They described their discoveries in the journal Evolution and Human Behavore, and they can be briefly read in a press release of the University of California in Santa Barbara.
The angry expression of the face - moved and lowered down the eyebrows, drawn into a thin line of lips, crushed nostrils - is the same in all cultures and is made by children who are blind from birth who have never seen it, notes the lead author of the study, Aaron Sell.
As part of a major research project on the nature of anger, scientists have found that this emotion has emerged to deal effectively with disputes during conflict.
The more physical harm one person may cause to another, the more ability he has to dictate his circumstances, and the more he reports it to the householder by means of anger.
Researchers have found support for another hypothesis: physically strong people are more likely to become angry and to move to action, feel that they have the power to impose conditions that are not suitable for them, and prefer to use force to resolve conflicts in a peaceful manner.
In view of the fact that anger is primarily “the emotion of the tender”, scientists have decided that the movements of each of the seven groups of muscles that create the angry expression of the person should make the angry individual more powerful and dangerous in the eyes of the interlocutor, thereby making him accept his conditions as soon as possible in order to avoid conflict.
To test this hypothesis, researchers simulated on the computer the persons where each of the seven elements of the angry person was present or missing, and showed them to the informers.
While the lost eyebrows or forward-looking chins did not individually make a person wicked, the physical participants who were represented with such characteristics recognized the strength of the study as unanimous.
Man’s anger, like that of animals, poses a threat: an exaggerated display of his own strength, forcing him to accept and obey.
A man crushes his nostrils and squeezing his lips for the same purpose as a plumbing frog, or baboon, that shows its ticks.
“Gneve “starts” by refusing to accept the situation and the person immediately takes the form that best demonstrates the consequences of the refusal.
But the most amazing thing is that none of the components of an angry person is arbitrary, they all express the same thing," noted Anthropologist John Tuby.
Mincomms proposed to allocate 250 million Crim radio transmission roubles
Mincombs proposed to allocate 250 million roubles from the federal budget to the autonomous non-profit organization Krim in 2014.
This is referred to in a draft Government Regulation prepared by an agency that has studied Lenta.ru.
According to the explanatory note to the project, subsidies from the federal budget will be directed “to cover the costs of creating a wide-ranging coverage of the socio-economic situation and the development of modern information space in the territory of the Republic of Crimea, including the acquisition of equipment”.
In particular, it is planned to convert the hardware studio unit, video walls, central hardware and video server.
The acquisition of a mobile television station and a satellite sender is also planned.
In addition, the company will pay for the use of the fibre-optic link (VOLS) and for the renovation of the energy system.
Grants will be provided within the framework of the federal budget provided for by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs.
The State Broadcasting Company Crimea was established in 1959 and broadcasts in seven languages: Ukrainian, Russian, Crimean, German, Greek, Bulgarian and Armenian.
To date, over 75 per cent of the peninsula has been reached on television.
In 2011, the Crimea Television Company obtained a digital television license.
